== Banana Skin

When practicing swung subdivisions with a focus on movement and muscular action,
as outlined above, an algorithmic process unfolds, generating unexpected or
non-pre-audiated results. This occurs because the body's motion dictates the
rhythmic outcome rather than pre-heard musical expectations.

Furthermore, performers often encounter familiar rhythmic results — but produced
through an unfamiliar movement pattern. This mismatch between expected sound and
unexpected motion creates a perceptual contradiction, disrupting focus and
timekeeping.

I refer to this phenomenon as the "banana skin effect" — a momentary slip in
rhythmic awareness caused by the dissonance between habitual pre-auditory
expectations and newly acquired movement patterns.